Question:
Store the squares of each number into a Set.
Input:
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4);

Solution:

Java 8 Streams store squares in a Set using map to square then collect(Collectors.toSet()). For input [2, 3, 4], produces Set {4, 9, 16} (duplicates auto-removed).

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream the list via stream(). Map each num to num * num square. Collect to Set<Integer> with Collectors.toSet() (HashSet impl).

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Set;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class SquaresToSet {
    public static Set<Integer> squaresToSet(List<Integer> numbers) {
        return numbers.stream()
                      .map(num -> num * num)
                      .collect(Collectors.toSet());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4);
        Set<Integer> squares = squaresToSet(list);
        System.out.println(squares);  // [4, 9, 16] (order not guaranteed)
    }
}

Prints {4, 9, 16} (HashSet unordered).

#Thought Process
map transforms to squares. toSet() collector deduplicates via hashCode/equals. Ideal for uniqueness; LinkedHashSet preservers order if needed via toCollection(LinkedHashSet::new).

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty Set.
Null list: NPE on stream().
Null elements: null * null NPE; filter nulls.
Zero: {0}.
Negatives: {4, 9} (-2â†’4).
Overflow: Int wraps; use Long map for safety. Duplicates input: Already unique squares.
